msg.data:
Welcome to Splice Machine ML

The data platform for intelligent applications

paragraphs.text:
%angular

What is machine learning?

msg.data: What is machine learning?

paragraphs.text: %md

msg.data: Machine Learning is the science of getting computers to learn and act like humans do, and improve their learning over time in autonomous fashion, by feeding them data and information in the form of observations and real-world interactions. Through a decision function, or a model, computers can learn relationships in data that we never had the ability to see or utilize in the past

Why use Splice Machine ML

Splice Machine ML isn't just a machine learning platform, it is much more than that. In fact, it is a complete machine learning lifecycle management solution, giving you total control of your models, from retrieving data to scalable deployment. Here are just a couple of advantages that we have over other platforms.

  1. Machine learning takes place on the incredibly powerful Apache Spark executors in your database, allowing you to complete massive jobs in parallel
  2. When using the Splice Machine Python Package, the PySpliceContext, Spark will have direct access to your large amount of data, reducing time that would be spent transferring billions of rows over JDBC
  3. An important part of data science is visualizing your data to find trends even before you feed it into an algorithm. Thanks to our handy Zeppelin notebooks, that can take place with one line of SQL code
  4. After a data scientist has created a model, we need to tweak our model's parameters (preprocessing, hyperparameters, data source tc.), in the aim of coming up with the best model. However, there is no good way to keep track of all of these tiny changes. Our solution is a platform called MLFlow, which allows you to version runs and compare them to each other.
  5. After you have found the best model for your task, you are ready to deploy it and use it in your applications. We allow you to push your MLFlow models up to scalable cloud computing services, such as AWS SageMaker and AzureML, to make predictions in real time.

Feeling overwhelmed? Don't worry, we are going to guide you through this process.

Your friends at Splice Machine

paragraphs.text:
%angular

How does this work?

msg.data: How does this work?

Zeppelin

Zeppelin notebooks are a simple, easy and intuitive way to do data science, right in your browser. It is fast because any Spark computations you run inside of the notebook are executed right on your cluster's Spark executors.

As if speed wasn't enough, Zeppelin notebooks also make machine learning easier. By using Zeppelin intepreters, you can run different languages inside the same notebook. The language you want to run is signified by a % sign followed by an interpreter name at the top of a cell. For example, two of the interpreters you will become very familiar with while using our platform are the %pyspark and %splicemachine interpreters. In the %splicemachine interpreter, using a simple SQL SELECT query, you can easily generate beautiful graphs that show you trends in your data, even before you import it into pyspark.

This entire demo was written inside a Zeppelin notebook

-Your friends at Splice Machine


MLFlow

As a data scientist, you are constantly tweaking parameters, in the hopes of achieving the best possible model. The issue with that, is that it is very difficult to keep track of what you are changing-- even increasing a parameter by one can improve your model dramatically. MLFlow is a solution to this problem.

MLFlow has two main concepts: experiments and runs. Each time you run a model, MLFlow will generate a new run, which you can keep track of in the MLFlow tracking UI. The markers that you write in your code will be visible in the UI, so you can easily compare runs to each other. Because a new run is logged each time you create a model, we highly reccomend that you only add markers after your model runs successfully..

You can think of experiments like folders for your models. For example, if you are an ecommerce company, you might have an experiment for predicting how late a shipment will be, and another for predicting which customer is the most likely to buy a certain item.

-Your friends at Splice Machine

paragraphs.text:
%angular

Importing Your Data



Importing Data into Splice Machine

The most ubiquitous file format for machine learning has traditionally been a CSV file. CSV files don't give you any of the awesome features that Splice Machine does, so we need to import our CSV file into a Splice Machine table. Here are some steps on how to do that:

  1. Upload your CSV file into an S3 bucket and give your cluster permission to access it via IAM. You can do this with the "reconfigure" option in the Cloud UI.
  2. Using the CREATE TABLE command, either in the SQL Shell or in the %splicemachine intepreter, create a table that conforms to the CSV's schema.
  3. In the Splice Machine intepreter (in Zeppelin), use the command CALL SYSCS_UTIL.IMPORT_DATA stored procedure. You can read more about this in our documentation
    -Looking forward to helping you, your friends at Splice Machine

paragraphs.title: Create banking table

%splicemachine

DROP TABLE IF EXISTS DEMO.BANKING;

CREATE TABLE DEMO.BANKING (
    AGE INT,
    JOB VARCHAR(40),
    MARITAL VARCHAR(40),
    EDUCATION VARCHAR(40),
    DEFAULT_CREDIT VARCHAR(20),
    BALANCE FLOAT,
    HOUSING VARCHAR(20),
    LOAN VARCHAR(20),
    CONTACT VARCHAR(40),
    DAY FLOAT,
    MONTH VARCHAR(20),
    DURATION FLOAT,
    CAMPAIGN FLOAT,
    PDAYS FLOAT,
    PREVIOUS FLOAT,
    POUTCOME VARCHAR(40),
    TERM_DEPOSIT VARCHAR(20)
);

paragraphs.text:
%angular

Visualizing Your Data



Data Visualization

As we mentioned before, visualizing your data is an extremely important part of machine learning. We can do this in the Splice Machine interpreter via a simple SQL SELECT query. Looking at informative graphs of our features can often influence which features we decide to use in the final model

Helpful Hint: the Splice Machine interpreter can be accessed with %splicemachine. Also ${a=default value} creates an input field in the Splice Machine interpreter. For this demo, we will use a breast cancer dataset which has already been imported into this cluster's Splice Machine Database.

With <3, Your Friends at Splice Machine

paragraphs.text:
%angular

Connecting to your database



Got the data imported? Awesome. Let's establish a connection to your database so we can use the table data for machine learning. To connect, we will use a protocol called JDBC (a Java based database connection protocol). We know this sounds complicated, but we take care of all of this stuff under the covers.

What we need from you is your JDBC connection string, which can be found on the bottom right of your Splice Machine Cloud UI. Make sure you add a user= and password= parameters to the end of the string. These arguments should be semicolon (;) sepperated with no spaces in between.

For example, one might look like:
jdbc:splice://amritsaccount-mlworkflow.splicemachine-qa.io:1527/splicedb;ssl=basic;user=▒▒▒▒▒▒▒▒▒▒;password=▒▒▒▒▒▒▒▒▒▒

-Great Job, your friends at Splice Machine

paragraphs.title: Get JDBC connection and create PySpliceContext
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark
from splicemachine.spark.context import PySpliceContext
def get_jdbc_url():
    import os
    framework = os.environ['FRAMEWORK_NAME']
    return 'jdbc:splice://{framework}-proxy.marathon.mesos:1527/splicedb'.format(framework=framework)
    
splice = PySpliceContext(get_jdbc_url(), spark)
splice

%angular

Introduction to MLFlow



Now that you supplied your JDBC URL (remember to press enter or your entry will not be saved), we would like to introduce you to MLFlow. Take a look at the Python sample below, and you should be able to understand the basic syntax of how it works.

msg.data:
Introduction to MLFlow



Now that you supplied your JDBC URL (remember to press enter or your entry will not be saved), we would like to introduce you to MLFlow. Take a look at the Python sample below, and you should be able to understand the basic syntax of how it works.

How to use MLFlow Markers

from splicemachine.spark.context import *
from splicemachine.ml.zeppelin import *
from pyspark.classification import DecisionTreeClassifier
from pyspark.feature import VectorAssembler

# In the below cell, there will be a form field for you to enter your experiment. 
   Upon pressing enter, it will be registered and submitted with MLFlow

# PLEASE NOTE: We highly reccomend that you add these markers after your model is working, so you don't fill up your runs with failures.

# We will now create a new run, so your model's metadata isn't overwritten

my_run = zeppelin.Run()

my_run.create_new_run()


# +---------CELL i---------+
# ...
# Now we can log a parameter (for example, a parameter might be the classifier, the number of training/testing samples etc.)
# Syntax: <my run variable>.log_param(parameter, value). Note value must be a string (you may use the str() method)

my_run.log_param("dataset", "SPLICE.SHIPPING_02_2018")


# +---------CELL i+1---------+
# ..
my_run.log_param("preprocessing", "string indexer, vector assembler")


# +---------CELL i + 3---------+
# ..
# Next, we have to log our classifier as an "artifact" to MLFlow. This allows us to import it later and predict, \
    and it also gives the ability for deploying it to SageMaker or AzureML (experimental)

# Syntax: <my run var>.log_model(<variable to our trained model>, 'pysparkmodel') # make sure you use the 'pysparkmodel' string as your second parameter!

my_run.log_model(fitted_decision_tree, "pysparkmodel")


# +---------CELL i + 4---------+
# ... 
# Lastly, we will log metrics about how well are model performs

 Syntax: <my_run_var>.log_metric(metric name, value). Note that value must be an integer or a floating point number


my_run.log_metric("F1 Score", model_f1_score)
my_run.log_metric("Accuracy", model_accuracy_score)
my_run.log_metric("MCC", model_matthews_corrcoef)


#+------------------+
To change a parameter, simply rerun the cell containing my_run.create_new_run, and run all of the cells below it!
# Congrats 🎉! You made it!

paragraphs.title: Start new run
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark
from pyspark.ml import Pipeline, PipelineModel
from pyspark.ml.feature import HashingTF, RegexTokenizer, StopWordsRemover, IDF
from pyspark.sql import SparkSession
from pyspark.conf import SparkConf
from splicemachine.ml.zeppelin import Run

#get and create the run
banking_run = Run()
banking_run.create_new_run()
#get df using PySpliceContext
banking_dataframe = splice.df('SELECT * FROM DEMO.BANKING')
#visualize the data
z.show(banking_dataframe)
#log parameters (for mlflow)
banking_run.log_param('dataset_samples', str(banking_dataframe.count()))
banking_dataframe.createOrReplaceTempView('banking')

paragraphs.title: Equalize (undersample) data
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark
from pyspark.sql.functions import rand

# Equalize the number of people who said "yes" to the number that said "no"

yes = sqlContext.sql("SELECT * FROM banking WHERE TERM_DEPOSIT='yes'") 
nos = sqlContext.sql("SELECT * FROM banking WHERE TERM_DEPOSIT='no' LIMIT {nos_count}".format(nos_count=yes.count()))

# Merge the two using a union
banking_dataframe = yes.union(nos)

# Create a temporary view so we can view how many samples we have in each class
banking_dataframe.createOrReplaceTempView('bank_filt')

# show in Zeppelin
z.show(sqlContext.sql('SELECT TERM_DEPOSIT, count(*) FROM bank_filt GROUP BY TERM_DEPOSIT'))

# randomize input order, so that we don't have any trends in our data
banking_dataframe = banking_dataframe.orderBy(rand())

banking_run.log_param('class_samples', str(yes.count()))

paragraphs.title: Index, encode and vectorize the data
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark
from pyspark.ml.feature import VectorAssembler, StringIndexer, OneHotEncoder

# Index jobs from strings to numbers, and turn those into binary variables
job_indexer = StringIndexer(inputCol='JOB', outputCol='INDEXED_JOB')
job_encoder = OneHotEncoder(inputCol='INDEXED_JOB', outputCol='ENCODED_JOB')

# Index marital status from strings to numbers, and turn those into binary variables
marital_indexer = StringIndexer(inputCol='MARITAL', outputCol='INDEXED_MARITAL')
marital_encoder = OneHotEncoder(inputCol='INDEXED_MARITAL', outputCol='ENCODED_MARITAL')

# Index education from strings to numbers, and turn those into binary variables
education_indexer = StringIndexer(inputCol='EDUCATION', outputCol='INDEXED_EDUCATION')
education_encoder = OneHotEncoder(inputCol='INDEXED_EDUCATION', outputCol='ENCODED_EDUCATION')

# Index default_credit
default_credit_indexer = StringIndexer(inputCol='DEFAULT_CREDIT', outputCol='INDEXED_DEFAULT_CREDIT')

# Index Housing
housing_indexer = StringIndexer(inputCol='HOUSING', outputCol='INDEXED_HOUSING')

# Index loans
loan_indexer = StringIndexer(inputCol='LOAN', outputCol='INDEXED_LOAN')

# Index previous outcome from strings to numbers, and turn those into binary variables
poutcome_indexer = StringIndexer(inputCol='POUTCOME', outputCol='INDEXED_POUTCOME')
poutcome_encoder = OneHotEncoder(inputCol='INDEXED_POUTCOME', outputCol='ENCODED_POUTCOME')

# Index whether subject opened a term deposit account
label_indexer = StringIndexer(inputCol='TERM_DEPOSIT', outputCol='label')

banking_run.log_param('preprocessing', 'strIdx, oneHot, vectorAssem')
# Define our features
features = [
    'ENCODED_JOB',
    'ENCODED_MARITAL',
    'ENCODED_EDUCATION',
    'INDEXED_DEFAULT_CREDIT',
    'INDEXED_HOUSING',
    'INDEXED_LOAN',
    'DURATION',
    'CAMPAIGN',
    'PREVIOUS',
    'ENCODED_POUTCOME'
]

# Vectorize
assembler = VectorAssembler(inputCols=features, outputCol='features')

paragraphs.text:
%angular

Pipeline & Model Creation



On a lower level, all operations on dataframes, including models are what we call dataframe transformations. DataFrame transformations take in a dataframe a return a new one with some change. We can chain these transformers together in something called a Pipeline object, which we can eventually apply to raw data and get out a prediction. It is common practice in the machine learning world to partition your data into "training" and "testing" datasets, in which the computer learns the relationship using the training dataset and is evaluated with the testing dataset. We evaluate our model by giving it only the input data from the testing dataset and compare its predicted output to the actual output. This allows us to create some meaningful metrics that help us evaluate our model. After we do that, we can assemble our pipeline and create our model using the training dataset

Don't give up! <3 your friends at Splice Machine

paragraphs.title: Choose our model (Decision Tree)
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark
from pyspark.ml.classification import DecisionTreeClassifier, RandomForestClassifier, NaiveBayes, GBTClassifier, LogisticRegression
from pyspark.ml import Pipeline

max_depth=5
max_bins=32

# create a decision tree classifier
classifier = DecisionTreeClassifier(maxDepth=max_depth, maxBins=max_bins) 

# define our pipeline stages
stages = [ 
        job_indexer,
        job_encoder,
        marital_indexer,
        marital_encoder,
        education_indexer,
        education_encoder,
        default_credit_indexer,
        housing_indexer,
        loan_indexer,
        poutcome_indexer,
        poutcome_encoder,
        label_indexer,
        assembler,
        classifier
    ]

banking_run.log_param('max_depth',max_depth)
banking_run.log_param('max_bins',max_bins)

banking_run.log_param('stages_num', str(len(stages)))

# get the name of the classifier, so when we change/try a new one, it will automatically add the correct name
banking_run.log_param('algorithm', str(classifier).split('_')[0])

# create a pipeline with our defined stages
bcPipeline = Pipeline(stages=stages)

paragraphs.text:
%angular

Train and Evaluate our Model



Once we have a trained model, we can evaluate it by comparing the actual predictions to the correct predictions. Using this, we can get some insight into how well our model performs via metrics such as F1 Score, Accuracy and Matthews Correlation Coefficient. It is also good practice to employ some sort of cross validation when evaluating your model to prevent a paradigm known as a overfitting. We use CV iteation averaging.

Train and Evaluate our Model



Once we have a trained model, we can evaluate it by comparing the actual predictions to the correct predictions. Using this, we can get some insight into how well our model performs via metrics such as F1 Score, Accuracy and Matthews Correlation Coefficient. It is also good practice to employ some sort of cross validation when evaluating your model to prevent a paradigm known as a overfitting. We use CV iteation averaging.

<3 your friends at Splice Machine

paragraphs.title: Train model (Decision Tree)
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark
from splicemachine.ml.zeppelin import SpliceBinaryClassificationEvaluator

# The number of iterations to rerun our model and average the results on
CV_ITERATIONS = 3  

# The percentage of the original dataset to use for training
TRAINING_SIZE = 0.7 

# setup a binary classification model evaluator 
evaluator = SpliceBinaryClassificationEvaluator(spark) 


# parallelize the data
banking_dataframe = banking_dataframe.repartition(10)

# Loop through iterations
for iteration in range(1, CV_ITERATIONS + 1): 
    print('ITERATION {iteration}'.format(iteration=str(iteration)))
    
    # Create training and testing dataFrame
    training, testing = banking_dataframe.randomSplit([TRAINING_SIZE, (1.0 - TRAINING_SIZE)]) 
    fittedPipeline = bcPipeline.fit(training)
    predictions_dataframe = fittedPipeline.transform(testing)
    
    # Select the actual and the predicted labels
    pred_v_lab = predictions_dataframe.select('label', 'prediction') 
    # Add to the evaluator so we can average the results of the n runs
    evaluator.input(pred_v_lab)

banking_run.log_model(fittedPipeline, ' pysparkmodel')

paragraphs.title: Evaluate model (Decision Tree)
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark

# show results
metrics = evaluator.get_results('dict')

for metric, value in metrics.items():
    print(metric, '-->', value)
    banking_run.log_metric(metric, value)

# The number of iterations to rerun our model and average the results on
CV_ITERATIONS = 3

TRAINING_SIZE = 0.7

# give it our splice machine spark/sql contexts, so it may calculate from your data
#evaluator.setup_contexts(sc, sqlContext)

banking_dataframe = banking_dataframe.repartition(10)

    print('ITERATION {iteration}'.format(iteration=str(iteration)))
    
    # Create training and testing dataFrame
    training, testing = banking_dataframe.randomSplit([TRAINING_SIZE, (1.0 - TRAINING_SIZE)]) 
    fittedPipeline = bcPipeline.fit(training)
    predictions_dataframe = fittedPipeline.transform(testing)
    
    # Select the actual and the predicted labels
    pred_v_lab = predictions_dataframe.select('label', 'prediction') 
    # Add to the evaluator so we can average the results of the n runs
    evaluator.input(pred_v_lab)

banking_run.log_model(fittedPipeline, ' pysparkmodel')
